            Feedbacks
**********************************************-->
<setup>
  <select name="correctFeedback" type="text">
    <option>Awesome!</option>
    <option>Great job!</option>
    <option>Fantastic!</option>
    <option>Nice work!</option>
    <option>Amazing!</option>
    <option>Excellent!</option>
    <option>Right on!</option>
    <option>Perfect!</option>
  </select>
</setup>
  <feedback condition="$basicCorrect or $correctPattern1 or $correctPattern2 or $correctPattern3 or $correctPattern4 or $correctAndZeroIntercept">$correctFeedback</feedback>
  <feedback condition="$notAnEquationInX"><p>It looks like this expression is missing an <m>x</m>.</p></feedback>
  <feedback condition="$noIntercept"><p>It looks like this expression is missing the slope-intercept.</p></feedback>
  <feedback condition="$ans15.numSubmissions > 2 and $ans15.creditAchieved != 1">
    <div name="helpText">
      <p>In this problem, we are given a known point on the line, along with the equation for a parallel line. Since the two lines are parallel, this means that their slopes are equal. Therefore, in order to write the equation of the line in <ref uri="https://open.lib.umn.edu/algebra/chapter/topic-4-5-slope-intercept-form-of-a-line/"><term>slope-intercept form</term></ref>, we need only calculate the <m>y</m>-intercept. To accomplish this, we can substitute the coordinates of the known point into the slope-intercept equation and solve for the unknown <m>b</m>.</p>
    </div>
  </feedback>


<!--*********************************************
            Hint
**********************************************-->
<hint name="helpSection"><title>Worked Example</title>

<p>Here is a similar worked example:</p>
<example newNameSpace>
<p><em>Find the equation of the line through the point <m>($a, $b)</m> and parallel to the line <m>y = <math simplify="numbersPreserveOrder">$m{simplify} x + $f</math></m></em></p>


<setup>
  <math name="a">2</math>
  <math name="b">12</math>
  <math name="c">3</math>
  <math name="d">8</math>
  <math name="e">4</math>
  <math name="f">5</math>
  <math name="m" simplify>($c$e)/($d)</math>
  <math name="yInt" simplify>-$c$e$a/$d + $b</math>
  <math name="correctEq">$m x + $yInt</math> 
</setup>

<p><em><alert>Solution.</alert></em></p>
<ul>
  <li>Since we are given the parallel line, we know that the slope must be <m>m = $m{simplify}</m>.
  <li>Determine the <m>y</m>-intercept, using the given point <m>($a,$b)</m>:
    <md>
  <mrow>y \amp= $m x + b \amp\text{slope-intercept form}</mrow>
  <mrow>$b \amp= $m \cdot $a + b\amp\text{substitute known values}</mrow>
  <mrow>$yInt{simplify} \amp= b \amp\text{simplify}</mrow>
</md></li>
<p>With known slope and <m>y</m>-intercept, we can now write the equation of the line:
  <me>y = $correctEq{simplify}.</me></p>
  </li>
</ul>

<p>We can check by graphing:</p>
  <graph grid xmin="-4" ymin="-4" xmax="10" ymax="20">
    <line fixed applyStyleToLabel labelPosition="left">y = $correctEq
      <label><m>y = $correctEq{simplify}</m></label>
    </line>
    <point name="knownPoint" fixed styleNumber="8" labelPosition="lowerright" applyStyleToLabel>($a,$b)
      <label><m>($a,$b)</m></label>
    </point>
    <point name="yIntDemo" fixed styleNumber="11" applyStyleToLabel labelPosition="left">(0,$yInt)
      <label><m>(0,$yInt)</m></label>
    </point>
    <line fixed applyStyleToLabel labelPosition="lowerRight" styleNumber="9">y = $m x + $f
      <label><m>y = $m x + $f</m></label>
    </line>
  </graph>
</example>

  </hint>
  

<!--*********************************************
            Solution
**********************************************-->
<solution>
<ul>
  <li>Since we are given the parallel line, we know that the slope must be <m>m = $m{simplify}</m>.
  <li>Determine the <m>y</m>-intercept, using the given point <m>($a,$b)</m>:
    <md>
  <mrow>y \amp= $m x + b \amp\text{slope-intercept form}</mrow>
  <mrow>$b \amp= $m \cdot $a + b\amp\text{substitute known values}</mrow>
  <mrow>$yInt{simplify} \amp= b \amp\text{simplify}</mrow>
</md></li>
<p>With known slope and <m>y</m>-intercept, we can now write the equation of the line:
  <me>y = $correctEq{simplify}.</me></p>
  </li>
</ul>
</solution>
</problem>


